        <heading>PREM. - MAR. LINK: RATEPAYER COSTS - DETAILS</heading>
        <speech by="#adf62df0-6616-4824-87bd-59fd0bc41914">
          <from>HON. JAMIE BAILLIE</from>
          <p>HON. JAMIE BAILLIE : Mr. Speaker, the CEO of Emera told Nova Scotians on Friday that the cost of the Maritime Link will increase from $100 million to $300 million by the time an application for that link is made to the Utility and Review Board here in Nova Scotia - that's a 25 per cent increase in the cost of this project. Nova Scotians are being asked to foot the bill for the Maritime Link, but they still don't know how much their electricity rate will be when electricity from Newfoundland and Labrador comes to their homes.</p>
        </speech>
        <speech by="#0768c045-71ae-4890-b6be-c52eb783ee95">
          <from>THE PREMIER</from>
          <p>THE PREMIER : Mr. Speaker, there will be a full rate filing and a full examination of the project by the Utility and Review Board. What was revealed on Friday was that this project would save the ratepayers of Nova Scotia between $300 million and $500 million. Would the Leader of the Progressive Conservative Party agree that if this is the case, this is the best project for Nova Scotia?</p>
